        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">What is the best SEO automation tool in 2026?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>It depends what you want automated. For full-stack autopilot (research, write, publish, optimise), theStacc at $99/mo replaces an entire content pipeline. For autonomous on-page fixes, Search Atlas OTTO. For SERP-driven content optimisation, Surfer SEO. For all-in-one suite work, SE Ranking. Most operators use one autopilot platform plus one suite for diagnostics.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Can SEO really be automated end to end?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Yes, the content side can — keyword research, brief generation, drafting, optimisation, and CMS publishing run hands-off on modern platforms. Technical fixes also have strong autopilot tooling now. Link building still benefits from human review. The honest answer: 80% of recurring SEO work can run on autopilot if you pick the right stack.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">How much do SEO automation tools cost?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Entry-level suites like SE Ranking start near $65/mo. Mid-market tools like Surfer SEO and Search Atlas sit at $89–$149/mo. Enterprise suites like Semrush and Ahrefs run $139–$499/mo. Done-for-you autopilot platforms like theStacc are $99/mo for 30 SEO articles published end-to-end.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Will Google penalise content from an automated tool?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Google's guidance is clear — content quality matters, not how it was produced. Automated content that is well-researched, original, and helpful ranks the same as hand-written content. The tools that get sites in trouble are spinners and thin-content generators, not modern autopilot platforms with research and editorial QA in the loop.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Do I still need a human SEO if I use automation tools?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>For most small and mid-market sites, no. A solid autopilot platform plus a monthly review by the founder is enough. Hire human SEO help when you have over 500 pages, complex enterprise rollouts, technical migrations, or competitive verticals like SaaS, finance, and legal that demand topical authority strategy.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">What is the difference between SEO automation and AI SEO?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>AI SEO is about the engine — using LLMs for ideas, drafts, and recommendations. SEO automation is about the workflow — chaining research, writing, optimisation, and publishing so a human does not have to. Most modern tools combine both, but a platform can be heavily AI-powered without being truly automated end-to-end.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Is theStacc better than Surfer SEO or Search Atlas?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Different jobs. Surfer optimises content you write. Search Atlas auto-fixes technical issues. theStacc runs the full content pipeline — research, brief, write, optimise, and publish — without you in the loop. If you want a tool, pick Surfer or Search Atlas. If you want articles published, pick theStacc.</p></div></div>
